metadata.name: Protozoan Triptych #1
metadata.description:
Under the microscope we can observe single-cell organisms - protozoa - growing and merging in a nutrient solution.

The microscope has an array of many different visualization modes available for use by curious investigators (24 in all!).

Press "1","2", or "3" to switch between the 3 main visualization modes.
Press "q" to switch between "quantized color" and "full color" modes.
Press "i" to switch between normal and inverse (or backlit) visualizations.

Press "r" to switch between portrait and landscape visualizations.

Press "4" to obtain a triptych of all 3 visualization modes at once.

Press "s" to save the current visualization as a png file.

Note: the previews take a few minutes to materialize. So be patient, and watch your protozoa grow and flourish!

Coding done completely in plain javascript.

objkt.name: Study of atom in analog, digital and A.I. #25

metadata.name: Study of atom in analog, digital and A.I. #25
metadata.description:
Experimental generative collection that merges analog photography, AI, generative text, and algorithmic coding, by digging down into the essence and building blocks of the different artistic communication channels. 

This work engages with all aforementioned mediums in a joint manner, guided by a random process. It starts with a collection of analog photographs, shot on film and scanned that were later used as a training dataset in Generative Adversarial Network (GAN) training. This way, A.I. learns the main characteristics of film photography. In particular, it mimics its recognizable grain. Another type of pixel grain is added with the use of code and pixel shifting as well as digital manipulation. Finally, the last type of “grain” appears with the use of generative text where a different kind of A.I. was given a short description of the project and instructed to imagine the rest of the story. The fragmented and void of meaning parts of generative text are added to the images as one of the possible traits.

issuer.name: Study of atom in analog, digital and A.I.

metadata.name: PixlFlippr #496
metadata.description:
PixlFlippr is an offshoot of my "Simple Harmonic Motion" series, inspired by the complexity of life emerging through the interaction of simple 'dumb' behaviors, with intricate details emerging on multiple scales. PixlFlippr operates on a pixel level (in the form of a GLSL frag shader).

Every pixel oscillates at a single fixed frequency, slightly out-of-sync with its neighbors. There is no explicit pixel-neighborhood communication (as there would be in eg Cellular Automata), and every pixel acts autonomously, oblivious to its surroundings. Yet collectively, the entire system exhibits constantly evolving complex high level behavior on many scales, ranging from patterns & behaviors spanning a few pixels, all the way up to the level of the entire image. These are further amplified through the emergent pixel aliasing artefacts & moiré patterns. 

Also, it's trippy af. 

PS All generative mints are a seamless loop with a loop duration ranging from a few minutes to over an hour. So stick around & watch it mutate!

metadata.name: Composition #3 Patchwork Quilt #153
metadata.description:
Abstract, non-square(!) composition based on textural strokes and noise. There are a lot of possible combinations with all of the features! 50% chance of two different palette sets. 50% chance to have a brush textured background, and a 50% chance of it being horizontal or vertical. The quadtree rectangles are based on poisson disc sampling based on a simplex noise field. 90% of the compositions will be smaller boxes, and 10% will be large. For each box, there is a 10% chance that it will be oriented opposite of the rest.

Press ’s’ to save a screenshot.

metadata.name: The Light of Summer #13
metadata.description:
Description of Seasons of Siskiyou Series
Surrounding my home, covering more than one million acres, is the Rogue River - Siskiyou National Forest which takes up three southern Oregon counties and one northern California county. It’s a magical place that fills the imagination and lifts the spirit; a place that inspires with its uniqueness, its legends, and its larger-than-life vistas.

Each season in the Siskiyou mountains is a unique experience unto itself. So, with an attention to the feelings this place evokes at any given time of the year, I designed four generative tokens to create an impression of the emotion–the calming quietness; the peaceful solitude; the overwhelming contrasts and variety of forms, shapes and textures; the magic and playful mystery; the welcomingness and foreboding. These four works feature clever and inventive creative coding techniques in a rich, graphic style to craft a stunning impression of the Seasons of Siskiyou.


Token 2 of 4 - THE LIGHT OF SUMMER (1990 x 1080) p5js Generative Token.
After weeks of a lengthening day, the color of spring gives way to the light of summer.  The air glows with the warmth of an apex sun; the coolness of the shadows welcomes tiny denizens; golden hues of drying flora frame the brilliance of lingering blooms.  Magic sails in solar breezes lazily drifting along with the whims of daylight.  Hike along remote trails, lose yourself in the unique beauty, and be immersed in the Light of Summer.

Output and Coding Features of “The Light of Summer”:

The Light of Summer features a variety of recursive algorithms to generate a range of plant forms.  The flowers are created with skewable vectored-ellipses to provide depth.  The output is generated by layering various generative systems using a one-point perspective.  An optical effect is applied to create atmosphere and accent-textures.  A radial gradient sets the background and frames the scene with a sense of atmosphere and humidity. 

Press DOWN ARROW to save the output as a png image file.

Each iteration varies the color palette, shape and density of the vegetation, the position and density of flowers and the optical-effect texture.

Token Published April 21, 2022 on FXHASH set at 75 Editions.
Written and designed by Ed Cavett using the p5js library.
Token 2 of 4 from the series “The Seasons of Siskiyou.”

metadata.name: Anagram #139
metadata.description:
'Anagram' explores the collision of nature with the modern world. Organic textures are generated within geometric boundaries to create a system of unique 'letters' that are combined and rearranged form a composition. Thirty-one texture types are possible, designed to work in five environments. Uncommon 'Assimilate' versions pull from the full texture set to represent the source 'word' of the generated Anagrams.

Artwork by 3dmanatee @3d_manatee. Made with p5js and ❤️.

metadata.name: Complementary Dot Logic #74
metadata.description:
Complementary Dot Logic was inspired by a series of OP Art paintings done by Victor Vasarely, called Code (Les Bleus). (c. 1967) Vasarely died in 1997 in the early days of computer art. I'm sure he would have embraced this medium. This is the sixth in a series of Vasarely inspired Generative Art pieces I am offering.

I became interested in Victor Vasarely's graphic artworks while I was in art school. As I struggled to learn computer graphics I wondered how do I write a program to produce imagery with a similar aesthetic? I call the process of creating algorithms inspired by other artists: "Art"ificial Intelligence.

My version of the composition has been expanded from the original 3 x 3 to 5 x 5 elements.  However, while there may be a grid of 5 x 5 squares in the composition there is a grid of 9 x 9 circles superimposed over the squares. 

First a random color is chosen for the overall background. Each square is drawn in its place in a random color and that color value is saved. On a second pass the circles are drawn, if they fall in the middle of a square they are rendered in that squares' complementary color. If the circle falls between the squares it is rendered in the background color appearing to alter the shape of the underlying square.

Again, there are many Gestalt interactions within this piece. The most prominent being the figure-ground relationship. The in-between background colored squares form a strong unifying structure, as do the other similar shapes. In Gestalt, similar shapes are seen together as a unifying whole.

Dr. Bill Generative Art OG @ drbillkolomyjec.com
